    "recap_headline": "United States Air Force Academy",
    "recap_text": "RENO, Nev., -\nAir Force (9-12, 5-1) clinched the series over Nevada (13-8, 4-2) with a finale win of 17-12 at Don Weir Field. With their second Mountain West series win of the season, the Falcons move into first in the conference standings. The Bird batters totaled 14 hits on the day while the pitchers combined for six strikeouts.\nTripp Garrish\nand\nWyatt Hanoian\nled offensively, with a trio of hits and four RBIs apiece.\nWalker Zapp\nlogged two hits for three runs batted in, while\nKayden Bradshaw\n,\nBen Niednagel\n,\nLuke Elmore\n,\nT.J. Oster\n, and\nCole Jenkins\nrecorded at least one RBI.\nIn his first start of the season,\nJordan Watkins\nthrew 2.2 innings with a strikeout and five earned runs allowed.\nEthan Dillinger\ntossed 1.1 relief innings, striking out a pair of batters and giving up one run. Following a three-run appearance for\nDavis Rhyne\n,\nMarcus Downing\nwent one scoreless inning on the mound. Junior\nSam Hentges\n(1-0) earned his first win of the season for his strikeout and run allowed on the bump. To close,\nEaston Miller\nthrew two strikeouts for a scoreless bottom of the ninth.\nEarly in the top of the first, the Birds took a 2-0 lead. With one out,\nBen Niednagel\ndrew a walk and advanced on a\nWyatt Hanoian\nsingle up the middle. Both runners scored when\nTripp Garrish\nsent a double out to shallow left field.\nThe Wolf Pack responded with a pair of their own runs to level the board at 2-2.\nAir Force put up a six-spot, 8-2, in the top of two. Leadoff batter, Boyd, opened with a triple and was joined on base by a walked\nT.J. Oster\n, who then stole second. With one away,\nKayden Bradshaw\nrecorded an infield single to third that sent Boyd across the plate. A walk to Niednagel loaded the bases for an RBI single from\nWalker Zapp\n. Back-to-back RBI hits by Hanoian and Garrish plated a trio of runs, before a Bradshaw RBI groundout scored the final run of the frame.\nIn the bottom of two, Nevada scored one run, 8-3.\nThe Pack made it a one-run game, 8-7, before Dillinger got out of the frame with a looking strikeout in the bottom of the third.\nNevada scored four runs in the bottom of the fifth to pull ahead 11-8.\nThe Falcons made it a one-run game but still trailed, 11-10, in the top of six. Walks and a wild pitch for Bradshaw and Niednagel put runners in scoring position. Zapp sent a sacrifice fly to right while Hanoian marked an RBI groundout to send both Falcons across the plate.\nThe visitor's seventh saw the Birds reclaim the advantage at 14-11. After Elmore singled and Boyd walked, the pair executed a double steal before Oster loaded the bags on a walk. Pinch hitter,\nCole Jenkins\n, enabled one run to score with a single to centerfield. Bradshaw and Zapp recorded sacrifices while Niednagel doubled to plate three.\nGarrish logged the only homer of the series for Air Force to extend their lead in the top of the eighth. Elmore made it to second on a walk and a stolen base and was brought home with an Oster single for a 16-11 lead.\nAir Force closed the top of the ninth at 17-11 after Zapp singled, stole second, and scored on a Hanoian single.\nThe Pack responded with one run for a final score of 17-12, in the bottom of the last frame.\nThe Falcons will be back in action for a rematch with Oral Roberts on Wednesday March 25 at 6 p.m. CT/5 p.m. MT in Enid, Okla.",
